latestPosts.caption:
Pilea peperomioides care: but first, swipe ➡️ to see it when I first bought it back in Jan 2018. 🥰🌱

My tips:

Get it in a spot out of the hot sun but where it can still see a large view of the sky. I prefer an east or north window (or some variation of that).

Wait until it’s pretty root bound to pot up. The roots are very delicate and it’ll struggle if you move it too often.

Water when completely dry but soak it completely when you do. A drain hole is non-negotiable. An airy chunky mix is preferred.

Fertilize while it’s growing, mine grows all year so I fertilize with foliage pro all year every time I water. Comment ‘fertilizer’ for the link.

Drop any questions you have in the comments! 🫶🏻

Are you scared to fertilize like I used to be? I’m telling you, one of the BEST things you can do for your plants is FEED THEM.

Foliage Pro has a higher nitrogen ratio which means it’s perfect for plants grown for their foliage (hello, that’s basically ALL of our houseplants). 

I use 1 tsp per gallon every time I water every single plant year round. Now — if you’re still nervous you can use 1/2tsp per gallon and work up if needed.

If you know your plants are getting the light they need but they’re still stagnant and sad, try this fertilizer!

Just comment ‘GROW’ below & I’ll send it to your inbox.

If you’ve been around for a while you know I’ve been raving about this fertilizer for years. It’s truly a holy grail product!! 🙌🏻

Aralia Fabian, one of my biggest regrets — but it’s not what you think! 

I regret selling this plant SO much. I love it and I miss it and I haven’t been able to find another big one locally. 

They’re so fun, but their care is similar to a fiddle leaf fig. Lots of bright light, water when bone dry. 

One of the coolest things? As it grows, the plant naturally sheds lower leaves and takes on a more tree-like form. It becomes more sculptural with age — kind of like watching a living piece of art evolve over time.

Do you own one?

ON SALE 🙌🏻 comment ‘drop’ for the link!

When you see the product listing it’ll look like a tub of powder, but the dropper bottle you see me using ships inside the tub! 

You just need one drop per gallon of water. Use it every time you water on EVERYTHING to control gnats.

One adult gnat can lay over 200 eggs. When they inevitably find their way into your home you want the soil to have this bacteria in it. 

The bacteria attacks fungus gnat larvae, breaking the life cycle.
